ich has influenced personally—discuss how his life and thought have affected conceptualization, study, and practice of psychotherapy, notions about education, ideas concerning the historical development of the text, perceptions of technology, as well as other topics. All of Illich's books are discussed and his ideas on education, theology, technology, anarchism, and society are examined in relationship to those of René Girard, Karl Polanyi, Emmanuel Levinas, and Jacques Ellul. Illich's previously unpublished paper offering a new view of conspiracy in European history is included.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aSociologyxPhilosophy. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aBottomley, Gesine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyars, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurkart, Eugene J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuden, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupuy, Jean-Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalbel, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarias, Domenico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzpatrick, Joseph P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarrigós, Alfons, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoinacki, Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoinacki, Lee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHulbert, Alastair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIllich, Ivan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKugel